But you forget MatPat, prime video isn't separate from just regular Amazon Prime. I wouldn't buy Amazon Prime just to watch some show that's on Prime Video: but I don't have to. My family already has Amazon Prime because of free shipping and it gives you discounts at Whole Foods now too. So that new Middle Earth show that's coming out? I won't be paying anything more than I'm already paying to watch it. A LOT of people already have Amazon Prime, they just don't use it for watching TV yet. But they will.

The Middle Earth fandom makes the Star Wars fandom look like a university club. IF they can make something the fans are happy with, the viewing numbers on that show are going to dwarf those of The Mandalorian. Sure, that won't be cheap: but if they do it right, it won't be as expensive as Game of Thrones Season 8 either.

snippet.textDisplay:
Pat (I doubt you will see this but) I think there are some oversights in your analysis. For starters amazon got in the business not necessarily to make top tier content but to drive business to their site and get in the circles of influential people who can pedal their overall agenda. When you look at it that way, everything else starts to make sense as far as they're concerned. The other thing you overlooked is Netflix is hosted on AWS, which amazon owns. This puts amazon in an interesting position, they may not have user telemetry data per se (because amazon engineers would never look at client data, wink wink nudge nudge) but they doo have access to the data netflix generates from the platform running. That alone gives them a wealth of information on the product. Fun fact if you got both prime video and netflix, you're technically paying amazon twice haha, nevertheless i digress. So from AMZN POV what they have works and they do not need to do much else, they can use their playbook of watching what works than build a competitor that will slowly choke the original competitor like an anaconda killing its prey. If netflix was to fold my money is it's probably going to end up getting bought by amazon, which is the next move in their playbook btw. Choke it until it can no longer fight back then consume it whole, you know like any constructor reptile.

Now the cable companies arent hurting either, i am specifically referring to the big boys (e.g., comcast, verizon, at&t, etc.). Yes the cable subscription are down however those cable giants also own another important segment...they also function as ISPs or Internet Service Providers. Now you might read that line and think but wait I live in insert-town-here, State I dont have any of those three anywhere near me. What you may not realize is smaller cable companies often outsource some of their infrastructure to the big boys, So just because your cable box says RCN on it, does not mean the the box was actually made by them. Or the backbone the local ISP connects to might be owned by one of those bigger names i previously mentioned. Furthermore, your VOD subscription will require internet, so you are still stuck dealing with the cable giants just this time in another way.

Lastly, when it comes to bundling cable companies have tons of experience with that. So I foresee the big cable giants simply offer bundles of subscription services at a "lower price". Either that, or they will buy or build companies that will specialize in that and simply resell you the content under that shell company name.


P.S You are right, prime video and a lot fo the new comers have TERRIBLE UI!
P.S.S Ethical disclosure, I am an employee of one of those big cable names but I am commenting as a customer, not an employee

snippet.textDisplay:
I feel like I need to say this for everyone's benefit...PLEX. Don't sleep on it! You casually threw it in a graphic, but it's really not like any other streaming service because it's yours. TLDR: everything you own in your own Netflix style library but better because you picked it all out.


So here's the long version, my family (all 7 of us) put all of our blu-rays, and DVD's, and digital movies together and created a library of over 400 movies, including many TV shows we all love, the Office, Big Bang, etc. We bought most of this content on sale at various vendors and everything goes into PLEX. Now we have our own streaming channel with only the stuff we want to watch. The con here is the process of setting it all up is time-consuming and somewhat technical (though basic for most people 35 years and below). It's portable, has a great app, and curated by us so we love the selection. It's really been better than Netflix. For $99 you can get a lifetime subscription, done and done.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm so glad you mentioned YouTube TV.
I've had it for like a year and a half.
I love it. I do wish they had a few more channels, but they have BBCA which is great. And they have a ton of shows available OnDemand, weirdly they even have shows from channels they don't even have available to watch live.
It really does feel like it's just cable on Wi-Fi, but I mean that in the best way possible bc it's cheaper and a set price, it has unlimited DVR space, you can log in anywhere, you can share it, plus no bills or surprises--apart from them upping their price with like 1mo notice that once, which I'm still kind of pissed about bc it should've gone up $10 at a time not $20 all at once. Unless I'm remembering incorrectly lol. I was bummed that they upped the price so much, and with very little notice. It's been awhile but I swear it was originally $35/mo before jumping to $55+/mo (I remember because I switched to YouTube TV from Hulu Live basically because it wasn't just cheaper but it seemed to--and it turns out absolutely does--have way better features like unlimited DVR space and tons of OnDemand shows/movies and channels like BBCA without me having to pay extra for it).
Anyway, I like it a lot.
